It’s not every day that you turn your grandmother into a hologram in Hollywood ✨

One of the hardest things for me is to listen to my grandmother talk about her experiences as a teenager in Japanese American Concentration Camps. She tells this one story about how when she was finally released (after over 3 years) she was put on a one way train out of the desert and told by our government that a motel had been given a voucher to house her. When she finally got there with another girl, the owner denied them shelter. 

Not only were they little girls (American citizens who had their homes, property, and everything else stolen from them and their families), but they also faced so much racism that they’d been imprisoned behind barbed wire in our country’s most unforgiving landscapes…and then denied basic shelter and human dignity yet again. It always makes me shutter to think about how much danger they were in when the safest option was to go back to the train station and wait for morning.

When a man approached them, my grandmother was alarmed, but he reached into his pocket and gave her a candy bar. She said that was the first time in 3 years that someone from the “outside” had acknowledged her as a human being and it gave her a tremendous amount of strength (and it’s also the reason why she believes small acts of kindness are sometimes the greatest).

It’s stories like these that made me question in middle school why I had our constitution memorized when its protections didn’t apply to people like me. When “non-alien” also meant “no longer a citizen” when skin color was more of a protection then birth place, law, and basic human rights. It’s this feeling of gaslit generational trauma that solidified my determination as a little girl to get myself into spaces where I could ensure no one else in my country ever felt that way again (a goal that seems increasingly further).

Grateful, relieved, and excited that in the near future you’ll be able to talk to my grandmother too through her hologram at @jamuseum

A Japanese-American girl born and raised in Washington, D.C. There’s a 100% chance you can guess my favorite tree 🌸

Although they’re beautiful, the part I cherish the most is that they’re a friendship gift from Japan to the U.S. A friendship that I’ll always strive to protect and strengthen. A common misconception is that the 3,000 trees were given post WWII, but they were actually brought over around 30 years earlier in 1912 on behalf of the Mayor of Tokyo. A process facilitated by our First Lady at the time, Mrs. Taft 🇺🇸🇯🇵
Some would say it’s an obsession, but I’m ok with that ☺️ @masterclass

This race will forever be one of my most epic in my mind. Even though I was on “vacation” and it was the weekend, I’d pulled an all-nighter the night before to help someone out at work and was so depleted that I miscounted my running laps… twice (luckily I wasn’t the only one though 😂). There’s something so special about racing through European streets from the hills, to the cobblestones, to the spectators shouting in different languages. J’adore Dior 🤍

Admittedly, my love for fashion began as a kid when I’d cut out my designs in paper form. However, I didn’t particularly like designer brands because they’d always felt inaccessible to me. It wasn’t until I attended fashion school that my perception and understanding evolved to one of complete admiration and inspiration.

You might wonder how a kid who hated designer brands ended up at fashion school… and that to me was obvious. I was obsessed with public policy and economics and one of the greatest predictors and indicators of both is fashion trends and sales. It was clear to me during college and my career that my counterparts didn’t understand the true impact and power of this intersection, which made me all the more interested. 

Similar to how policy is useless without proper design, so are clothes. From hemlines, to Birkin multiples, to sustainability trends, to lipstick… you have a nuanced picture on the economy. From corsets, to pants, to hats, to gloves… you have an intricate canvas of women’s rights and transformative social movements. From the way I heard one industry talk about the other, I developed empathy for why they simultaneously feel isolated and superior to each other and vice versa…

To me, it comes down to separate worlds that hold the key to each other and a never ending treasure trove of envisioned dreams and inspirational realities ✨

Something about turning a year older at midnight in Paris >>> 🥹✨

The craziest thing to me is that 2 months before this I didn’t even know I’d be in Paris for the summer and a few days before I didn’t even have anything planned for my birthday. It wasn’t until our dear friend came to visit us and told us she had a reservation at the hardest restaurant to get into in Paris that I realized this was the bday I had saved in my vision board album for years. “Realistically” though I’d told myself it probably wouldn’t happen till I was much older because I’d be busy working or doing something else.

Slowly starting to embrace that you’re always exactly where you’re supposed to be. Sometimes giving up control (as stressful as that is) makes your dreams manifest faster because then they’re more authentic and aligned with you 🫶🏼
